## 3. Why Existing LLM Interfaces Fail for Skill Building

This is the core design insight behind the product.

General-purpose AI chat interfaces are optimized for helpfulness. They validate your thinking, offer suggestions when you get stuck, and correct you gently when you go wrong. This makes them excellent for exploration and information retrieval. For skill building under pressure, it makes them counterproductive.

**Helpfulness undermines productive struggle.** Learning a complex skill requires encountering difficulty and working through it. When a model hints at the next step or validates a partial answer, it removes the struggle before the learning can happen. The user finishes the session feeling good about an answer they did not actually earn.

**Conversational AI tends to overvalidate.** Models are trained to be agreeable. In a mock interview context, this means they say "great point" when the point was shallow, accept a user segment without probing whether the choice was justified, and move forward when they should push back. This creates false confidence, the most dangerous preparation outcome because it is invisible.

**Without consistent evaluation criteria, scores are meaningless.** A general AI evaluating an interview answer will produce different scores on different days for the same quality of response. If a user cannot trust that a 3.2 means the same thing across sessions, the score cannot drive behavior change. And if the score cannot drive behavior change, tracking progress is theater.

**Tutoring reduces transferability.** When AI explains what step you should be on, you learn to follow instructions in that specific context. In a real interview, there are no instructions. The skill that actually transfers is knowing which step to apply and when, without being told. A system that guides you through the framework teaches framework familiarity. A system that withholds guidance and then evaluates your choices teaches judgment.

Study Notebook is designed around these constraints. The AI interviewer does not help during a session. Scoring is anchored to explicit behavioral signals per step, not overall impression. The learning profile persists across sessions so that improvement is measurable and consistent. The walkthrough teaches the mental model before the practice session requires you to apply it independently.

