## 7. Why the Architecture Supports the Product Goals

**Statelessness as a deliberate product decision**

The backend is fully stateless. Every API call receives the complete conversation history. No session state is stored server-side. This decision was made for two reasons that matter to the product, not just the infrastructure.

First, it means the AI evaluator always works from the full context of a session, not a compressed summary. Scoring accuracy depends on having access to every message the user sent, including early clarifications that informed later answers. A stateful backend that stores only partial context would produce less reliable scores.

Second, statelessness makes the conversation portable. A session in progress lives in the React state on the user's device. If the user closes the tab or refreshes, the session is gone, which is intentional. This is a practice tool. Incomplete sessions are not recoverable by design, which creates a mild commitment mechanism: starting a session means finishing it.

**Serverless persistence for the learning loop**

The learning profile, session history, scores, and habits are persisted in Azure Cosmos DB with a serverless capacity model. The serverless choice was made because the usage pattern, a single user doing one to two sessions per day, is exactly the pattern serverless is designed for. Provisioned throughput carries a cost floor regardless of usage. Serverless scales to zero when nothing is happening, which for a personal tool is most of the time.

The persistence itself is not incidental. It is what makes the adaptive system possible. A tool that forgets your scores after each session cannot adapt to your weak areas. Persistence is the mechanism by which practice sessions accumulate into a learning trajectory rather than remaining isolated events.

**Latency and the two-model split**

Case generation happens before the session begins, so latency is acceptable. The user sees a loading state while the case is constructed. GPT-4o-mini is fast and the structural constraints on the output are tight, so generation is reliable and quick.

The live interviewer is a different constraint. Streaming is used here because a blank screen while GPT-4o reasons through a response breaks the conversational feel. A real interviewer responds in seconds. Streaming gives the user a visible response within one to two seconds even when the full message takes longer to generate. This is a UX requirement that shaped the API implementation.

**The cost ceiling**

The entire system runs within Azure's free and near-free tiers. Static Web Apps, Cosmos DB serverless, and Azure Functions all have tiers that cost nothing at single-user scale. The only real cost is model inference, which at daily usage runs between three and five dollars per month. This ceiling was explicit in the design. A tool built for a job seeker should not create meaningful ongoing expense during the job search period.

